import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NUMBERS = {
    "27": {
        "1": "<p>The daughters of Zelophehad appear at a critical moment: the census of ch26 has just assigned land by family heads with male names, and no provision exists for a man who dies with daughters but no sons. The five daughters — Mahlah, Noah, Hoglah, Milcah, and Tirzah — are named as individuals, unusually specific in a text that often refers to women collectively or anonymously. Their full genealogy (Zelophehad → Hepher → Gilead → Machir → Manasseh) establishes their legitimate lineage within a major tribe, giving their claim maximum legal standing.</p>",
        "2": "<p>They stand before (<em>wayyaʿămōḏnâ lip̄nê</em>) Moses, Eleazar, the leaders, and the whole congregation — the full public judicial assembly at the sanctuary entrance. Ancient legal proceedings required public witnesses; presenting the claim before the entire assembled community transforms a family dispute into constitutional law. The location — the tent of meeting's entrance — places the claim in the divine court, not merely before human judges.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The daughters establish two facts: (1) their father died from his own sin, not from Korah's rebellion (<em>bəʿăḏat Qōraḥ lōʾ-hāyâ</em>); and (2) he left no sons. The first point matters legally: Korah's rebels and their households were destroyed (<em>yibbālēʿ</em>, 16:33), which may have forfeited their inheritance rights entirely. Zelophehad's ordinary death in the wilderness keeps his lineage's land claim intact; only the succession mechanism is missing.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The daughters' argument: <em>lāmmâ yiggāraʿ šem-ʾāḇînû mittôk mišpaḥtô</em> — why should our father's name be diminished from his clan? The inheritance of land is the perpetuation of family identity; land without an heir means the family name is erased from tribal memory. The appeal is not purely economic but genealogical-covenantal: every family was to have its place in the tribal inheritance of the promised land, and that place should not disappear due to an accident of birth.</p>",
        "5": "<p><em>wayyaqrēḇ Moshe ʾet-mišpāṭān lip̄nê YHWH</em> — Moses brought their case before YHWH. The verb <em>qāraḇ</em> (draw near) is used for priestly approach; Moses here acts as the supreme legal mediator. He does not decide the case himself but refers it to divine judgment. This referral pattern — used also in the Sabbath-breaker case (Num 15:34) and the Passover impurity case (Num 9:8) — shows the development of Mosaic case law as responsive divine revelation rather than systematic pre-established code.</p>",
        "6": "<p>YHWH's direct response through Moses establishes the divine validation of the daughters' claim. The legislative response is in two parts: an immediate ruling for this specific case (v7) and a general inheritance law for future cases (vv8-11). The specific case generates the general principle — characteristic of the casuistic (case-law) legislative style of P material throughout Numbers.</p>",
        "7": "<p><em>kēn ḇənôt Ṣəlop̄ḥāḏ dōḇərôt</em> — the daughters of Zelophehad speak rightly. The divine affirmation is unequivocal. YHWH does not merely permit their request; he declares them to be right. The inheritance shall pass to them, and their father's possession shall transfer through them. The ruling is immediately implemented: give them a hereditary possession among their father's brothers.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The general rule: if a man dies without a son, his inheritance passes to his daughter. The rule creates a hierarchy: son → daughter → brothers → father's brothers → nearest clan relative. This hierarchy expands the inheritance options well beyond the default male-primogeniture norm, while maintaining patrilineal structure. ANE parallel: Code of Hammurabi §§171-174 allowed daughters to inherit as malkatum in certain circumstances; Middle Assyrian Laws §§29-33 addressed daughter-inheritance from childless fathers. Israel's ruling goes further in explicitly validating daughters' claims as equal to sons' in the absence of male heirs.</p>",
        "9": "<p>If no daughter exists, inheritance passes to the brothers. The sequence ensures that land remains within the closest possible kinship circle before passing to more distant relatives — land was not simply property but the material form of covenant inheritance, the family's portion in the promised land. The loss of land to unrelated parties would represent a covenant failure.</p>",
        "10": "<p>If no brothers, to the father's brothers (uncles). The kinship succession model mirrors the <em>gōʾēl</em> (kinsman-redeemer) pattern of Leviticus 25 and Ruth, where the closest available male relative had both the right and obligation to redeem family property. The inheritance succession law and the redemption institution are complementary structures for keeping land within its covenant-assigned family lines.</p>",
        "11": "<p>If no father's brothers, to the nearest relative in the family. The phrase <em>lišʾērô haqqārōḇ ʾēlāyw</em> — to the one nearest to him from his family — allows for the extension of inheritance to any identifiable family connection rather than letting the land revert to tribal common land. This is declared a <em>ḥuqqat mišpāṭ</em> — a statute of judgment — permanent for all Israel. The case of Zelophehad's daughters thus became constitutional inheritance law, cited later in Josh 17:3-6 when they claimed their allotment.</p>",
        "12": "<p>YHWH commands Moses to ascend the Abarim mountains — the range culminating in Nebo/Pisgah, from whose height Canaan is visible. The viewing of the land before death is structured as a gift within the judgment: Moses cannot enter, but he may see. The land remains as real and promised as ever; Moses's personal exclusion does not diminish the promise's certainty for the generation that will cross.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Moses will be gathered to his people (<em>wəneʾesap̄tā ʾel-ʿammekā</em>) as Aaron was gathered to his (20:24-29). The parallel construction frames Moses's death as a completion parallel to Aaron's — the two founding leaders of the exodus generation will die in the same wilderness, by the same divine appointment, before the same land they served toward. The phrase marks death as a covenant homecoming rather than mere biological ending.</p>",
        "14": "<p>The reason for Moses's exclusion is stated again: rebellion against YHWH's command at the waters of Meribah-Kadesh. The specific charge — <em>mərîtem ʾet-pî</em> — you rebelled against my mouth — uses the word for speaking against divine command. The phrase <em>ləhaqdîšênî</em> — to sanctify/display my holiness — restates Num 20:12's verdict: Moses's failure was not merely disobedience but a failure to communicate YHWH's character accurately before the congregation.</p>",
        "15": "<p>Moses's response to his own death sentence is to pray for a successor — not to appeal the verdict, not to grieve, but to intercede for the community he has led. This self-forgetting intercession after personal judgment defines Moses's character: the man who cannot enter the land still cares more about who will lead the people into it than about his own fate.</p>",
        "16": "<p><em>yip̄qōḏ YHWH ʾĕlōhê hārûḥōt ləkol-bāśār ʾîš ʿal-hāʿēḏâ</em> — may YHWH, the God of the spirits of all flesh, appoint a man over the congregation. The address of God as <em>ʾĕlōhê hārûḥōt ləkol-bāśār</em> — the God who breathed life into all flesh — invokes the creator's authority over life and its Spirit, grounding Moses's request in the deepest possible theological claim: the one who gives the spirit of life to all humans can choose who carries his spirit for leading.</p>",
        "17": "<p>The qualifications for the successor: <em>ʾăšer-yēṣēʾ lip̄nêhem wǎʾăšer yāḇōʾ lip̄nêhem</em> — one who will go out before them and come in before them. The military leadership idiom (<em>yāṣāʾ... bāʾ</em> before the people) describes a commander who personally leads in battle rather than directing from the rear. The pastoral dimension follows: <em>wƏʾăšer yôṣîʾēm wǎʾăšer yəḇîʾēm</em> — who will lead them out and bring them in. Moses's concern is not succession of position but succession of shepherding character. The phrase <em>ʾăšer lōʾ-tihyeh ʿăḏat YHWH kaṣṣōʾn ʾăšer ʾên-lāhem rōʿeh</em> — so that YHWH's congregation will not be like sheep without a shepherd — became the canonical shepherd-without-leader image used by Ezekiel (34:5), Zechariah (10:2), and Jesus (Matt 9:36; Mark 6:34).</p>",
        "18": "<p>YHWH designates Joshua son of Nun — previously Moses's attendant (Exod 24:13; 33:11; Num 11:28) and one of the two faithful spies (Num 14:6-9,30,38) — as the successor. The qualification: <em>ʾîš ʾăšer-rûaḥ bô</em> — a man in whom the Spirit resides. This Sprit-qualification echoes the description of the 70 elders (Num 11:25-29) and anticipates the prophetic-Spirit theme in Joshua and the Judges. The laying on of hands (<em>səmiḵâ</em>) is the transfer gesture; in rabbinic Judaism this became the standard ordination ceremony (Sanhedrin 13b).</p>",
        "19": "<p>The commissioning must happen before Eleazar the priest and the whole congregation — public, witnessed, communal. The transparency of the succession prevents later disputes: everyone who will follow Joshua has witnessed his divine appointment. This public commissioning pattern becomes the template for subsequent leadership transitions: Moses commissions Joshua publicly (Deut 31:7-8,23), Samuel anoints David publicly (1 Sam 16:13), and the apostolic laying-on-of-hands in Acts follows the same communal principle.</p>",
        "20": "<p><em>wənātattā mêhôḏəkā ʿālāyw</em> — transfer some of your authority/majesty to him. The word <strong>הוֹד (hôḏ)</strong> — splendor, majesty, authority — describes the divine radiance that characterizes legitimate authority. Moses does not transfer all his authority (v21: Joshua will consult the Urim, while Moses spoke face to face) but enough for the congregation to obey. The partial transfer creates a hierarchy: Joshua is legitimate successor but not Moses's functional equal.</p>",
        "21": "<p>Joshua's consultative mode: he shall stand before Eleazar the priest, who will inquire for him by the <strong>אוּרִים (ûrîm)</strong> — the oracular objects kept by the high priest (Exod 28:30; Lev 8:8). The Urim and Thummim provided binary yes/no decisions in judicial and military matters; the high priest mediated the divine answer. Moses had direct divine access (YHWH spoke with him mouth-to-mouth, Num 12:8); Joshua operates through priestly mediation. This structural distinction marks the post-Mosaic period as one of more mediated revelation — a pattern that will characterize the entire Judges-Kings-Prophets era.</p>",
        "22": "<p>Moses executes the commissioning with full compliance: takes Joshua, presents him before Eleazar and the congregation. The compliance formula (<em>kaʾăšer ṣiwwâ YHWH ʾet-Moshe</em>) marks this as another act of covenantal obedience. In the act of commissioning his own successor, Moses models the humility of covenant leadership: the leader serves the community's future, not his own position's perpetuation.</p>",
        "23": "<p>The laying on of hands and commissioning complete the succession ceremony. Numbers ends in ch36; this appointment in ch27 functions as the theological turning point: from here, the narrative moves toward Moses's death and Joshua's entry. The ch27 Zelophehad ruling and Joshua commissioning are paired as law and leadership — the two things Israel needs most as it enters the land: just property law and capable, spirit-filled leadership.</p>"
    },
    "28": {
        "1": "<p>The festival offering calendar of chs 28-29 begins a new legislative unit addressing the <em>moadîm</em> — appointed times. These chapters supplement the calendar of Lev 23 with precise offering quantities that Leviticus does not specify. The placement of the calendar legislation here — after the census and before the Transjordanian campaigns — may reflect a preparation for settled land-worship after the conquest, or may be the narrative completion of the Sinai legislation that began in Leviticus.</p>",
        "2": "<p><em>ʾet-qorḇānî laḥmî ləʾiššay rêaḥ nîḥōḥî</em> — my offering, the food of my fire offerings, a pleasing aroma to me. The language frames the sacrificial system as YHWH's provision for his own communal meals with Israel — an ANE idiom where deity-worship involved the feeding of the god. The P tradition uses this language while simultaneously affirming that YHWH does not literally eat (Ps 50:12-13); the fire offering as pleasing aroma is a relational/acceptance metaphor, not a literal feeding. The command is stated as personal divine preference: observe at its appointed time.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The <strong>תָּמִיד (tāmîḏ)</strong> — the regular/perpetual offering — two yearling male lambs every day. The tamid became the institutional heartbeat of both Tabernacle and Temple; the Mishnah tractate Tamid describes the Second Temple's daily offering in minute detail across 7 chapters. In the post-Temple era, the morning and afternoon prayer services (Shacharit and Minchah) were understood to replace the tamid as the daily acts of covenant maintenance.</p>",
        "4": "<p>One lamb in the morning (<em>babbōqer</em>) and one at twilight (<em>bên hāʿarbayyim</em> — between the two evenings). The two-part daily offering structurally sanctifies the entire day: morning and evening frames enclose all human activity within the covenant acknowledgment. The Passover lamb was slaughtered at the same twilight time (Exod 12:6), connecting the daily maintenance offering to the founding redemptive sacrifice.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The grain accompaniment: one-tenth of an ephah of fine flour mixed with oil — matching the specifications of Num 15:4 for the lamb-sized grain offering. The consistency with ch15's graduated offering system integrates the tamid into the broader sacrificial framework. The tamid represents the minimum standard of daily covenant maintenance; all other offerings are additions to this baseline.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The tamid is characterized as <em>ʿōlat tāmîḏ</em> — the regular/perpetual burnt offering — established at Sinai (<em>hāʿăśûyâ bəhar Sînay</em>). The Sinai institution establishes the tamid as a permanent covenant obligation, not a later innovation. The phrase gives the daily offering its maximum authoritative grounding: it originated at the foundational covenant-moment and reflects YHWH's ongoing claim on each day of Israel's life.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The drink offering (<em>nesek</em>) for the tamid: one-fourth of a hin of fermented drink (<em>šēkār</em>). The specification of <em>šēkār</em> — strong drink, likely barley beer — rather than wine for the daily offering is unusual; most other offerings specify wine. This may reflect the availability of barley beer as the ordinary daily beverage in the ancient Near East versus wine as more festive; the tamid uses what is daily rather than what is special.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The evening lamb receives the same grain and drink offering as the morning lamb. The symmetry of morning and evening — identical sacrifices framing the day — creates a liturgical bracket: Israel begins and ends each day with the same act of covenant acknowledgment, making the entire day a continuous act of worship.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The Sabbath offering doubles the daily: two lambs plus a double grain offering. The Sabbath receives exactly twice the regular weekday offering, expressing the Sabbath's qualitative distinction through quantitative intensification. The doubled offering does not replace the tamid (v10) but supplements it; on the Sabbath, Israel brings both sets of offerings.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The Sabbath offering is in addition to (<em>ʿal</em>) the regular daily tamid and its drink offering. The additive structure of the festival calendar — each higher-level offering builds on rather than replaces the lower — creates a hierarchy of covenant intensity: daily offering + Sabbath addition + new moon addition + festival addition. The total offering burden increases with the occasion's significance.</p>",
        "11": "<p>The <strong>רֹאשׁ חֹדֶשׁ (rōʾš ḥōḏeš)</strong> — New Moon — offering: two young bulls, one ram, seven yearling male lambs. The lunar calendar governed the Israelite festival schedule; the new moon was both a calendar-reset marker and a monthly covenant celebration. New moon observance appears throughout the Hebrew Bible as a significant worship occasion (1 Sam 20:5,18,24-27; Isa 1:13-14; Amos 8:5; Hos 2:11), though not among the three pilgrimage festivals. The new moon offering is the most elaborate between the daily and the festival offerings.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The graduated grain offering quantities for the new moon follow the bull-ram-lamb scale established in Num 15: three-tenths for each bull, two-tenths for the ram. The consistent scaling across all occasions (daily, Sabbath, new moon, festivals) reflects the P tradition's unified sacrificial mathematics — the same proportional system applies regardless of the occasion's scale.</p>",
        "13": "<p>One-tenth of an ephah for each of the seven lambs at the new moon. The seven lambs — the number of completeness — in the new moon offering mirrors the seven lambs in the Sukkot offering (29:13ff) and in the Passover offering (v19), suggesting a structural connection between the monthly renewal and the major annual festivals.</p>",
        "14": "<p>The drink offerings at the new moon are specified with particular precision: half a hin of wine per bull, one-third of a hin per ram, one-quarter per lamb. The increase over the daily tamid quantities (one-quarter per lamb, v7) signals the new moon's elevated status. The total new moon drink offering exceeds the daily by a substantial amount, making wine consumption at the new moon a significant community event.</p>",
        "15": "<p>One male goat (<em>śəʿîr ʿizzîm ʾeḥāḏ</em>) as a sin offering at the new moon — the same sin-offering goat that appears at every festival throughout chs 28-29. The monthly sin offering cleanses the accumulated unintentional errors of the past month, providing a regular mechanism for communal purification between the major annual atoning events. The new moon became a minor but regular atonement moment in Israel's ritual calendar.</p>",
        "16": "<p>Passover (14th of the first month) is noted briefly as a single-verse marker — the instructions are already in Exod 12 and Lev 23:5. Chs 28-29 focus on the offering quantities, not the ceremony; Passover's ceremony is legislated elsewhere, while Numbers specifies only the sacrificial complement. The 14th day is the day of slaughter; vv17-25 cover the seven-day Unleavened Bread festival that follows.</p>",
        "17": "<p>The Festival of Unleavened Bread (Chag HaMatzot) begins on 15th Nisan and runs seven days. The combination of Passover (14th) and Unleavened Bread (15th-21st) creates an eight-day spring festival complex that Leviticus and Deuteronomy treat as a single integrated event. The removal of leaven from Israelite homes for seven days was a complete domestic purge — all traces of the old fermentation removed, signaling both the hasty departure from Egypt and the beginning of a new season.</p>",
        "18": "<p>The first day of Unleavened Bread is a <em>miqrāʾ-qōḏeš</em> — a holy assembly/convocation. The term <strong>מִקְרָא קֹדֶשׁ (miqrāʾ-qōḏeš)</strong> — literally a sacred calling — designates a day on which normal labor is prohibited and the community assembles for worship. Six of Israel's annual occasions carry this status: the first and seventh days of Unleavened Bread, Shavuot, Rosh Hashanah, Yom Kippur, and Shemini Atzeret (29:35).</p>",
        "19": "<p>The Unleavened Bread festival offering: two bulls, one ram, seven lambs — identical to the Shavuot offering (vv27), the Rosh Hashanah offering (29:2), and the Yom Kippur offering (29:8). The numerical uniformity of these four major offerings may indicate a common sacrificial template for major holy assemblies, with Sukkot's escalating bulls (29:12-38) representing a separate, more elaborate pattern.</p>",
        "20": "<p>The grain offerings follow the standard graduated scale: three-tenths per bull, two-tenths per ram. The festival grain offerings are substantially larger than the daily tamid's one-tenth, reflecting the festival's greater intensity of covenant acknowledgment. The precision of quantities across all festivals ensures that the calendar's sacrificial requirements are unambiguous and consistent.</p>",
        "21": "<p>One-tenth per lamb for the seven lambs of the Unleavened Bread offering. The seven lambs appearing consistently across major festivals (Unleavened Bread, Shavuot, Rosh Hashanah, Yom Kippur, Sukkot) create a numerical signature for covenant-celebration occasions — the number of completeness applied to the flock-offering as the standard festive sacrificial unit.</p>",
        "22": "<p>One male goat as sin offering during Unleavened Bread — the same sin-offering structure as the new moon and all major festivals. The goat sin offering provides the atoning dimension for each festival occasion: celebration of covenant blessing is paired with acknowledgment of covenant failure, ensuring that festival worship does not bypass the community's ongoing need for atonement.</p>",
        "23": "<p>All festival offerings are in addition to (<em>milelāḏ ʿōlat habbōqer</em>) the regular morning tamid. The additive structure means that on high-festival days the total offering burden was substantial — the daily tamid + Sabbath addition (if applicable) + festival offering all accumulate. This layering prevents festivals from replacing daily worship; they intensify the covenant relationship while the tamid maintains its continuous baseline.</p>",
        "24": "<p>The same pattern of food-offering repeats each of the seven days of Unleavened Bread. The seven-day repetition builds the festival's duration into the sacrificial calendar: the Exodus is not commemorated in a single day's offering but across a full week's repeated acts of covenant renewal. The repetition embodies the Unleavened Bread's theological point: the separation from Egypt's leaven is not a moment but a sustained orientation.</p>",
        "25": "<p>The seventh day of Unleavened Bread is also a holy assembly with no regular work — mirroring the first day (v18). The festival's boundaries are marked by matched holy assemblies, giving the entire week the character of a sacred bracket: enter with holiness, travel through seven days of offering, exit with holiness. The seventh-day holy assembly also recalls the Sabbath structure: seven days leading to a sacred culmination.</p>",
        "26": "<p>The Festival of Firstfruits — <em>Yôm habbikkûrîm</em>, identified here as the Day of Firstfruits — is what Exodus 23:16 calls the Festival of Weeks (Shavuot) and Deut 16:9-12 connects to counting seven weeks from the first harvest. The name <em>bikkûrîm</em> — firstfruits — frames Shavuot primarily as an agricultural thanksgiving: the first grain of the new harvest is presented to YHWH. The Septuagint calls it Pentecost (fiftieth day), reflecting the counting tradition of Lev 23:15-16.</p>",
        "27": "<p>The Shavuot offering: two bulls, one ram, seven lambs — identical to the Passover festival offering. The structural parallel between Passover and Shavuot in the Numbers calendar connects the spring grain festival to the spring exodus festival as components of a single covenant season. In Second Temple and early Christian interpretation, Shavuot at Sinai (when Torah was given) was linked to Shavuot in Acts 2 (when the Spirit was given) as fulfillment-of-type.</p>",
        "28": "<p>The grain offerings for Shavuot follow the same graduated scale as all major festivals: three-tenths per bull, two-tenths for the ram. The consistency of the offering math across all major festivals creates a unified sacrificial language; each festival speaks with the same numerical vocabulary while varying in duration, season, and ceremony.</p>",
        "29": "<p>One-tenth per lamb for the seven lambs of Shavuot. The seven-lamb signature applies here as throughout the festival calendar. The precision of one-tenth per lamb (rather than a total grain offering for all seven) reflects the individual accountability built into the offering system: each animal has its specified accompaniment.</p>",
        "30": "<p>One male goat for Shavuot's sin offering — the ubiquitous festival atonement offering. The goat sin offering's presence at every major festival (new moon, Passover week, Shavuot, Rosh Hashanah, Yom Kippur, each day of Sukkot) makes it the structural atonement companion to all festive celebration. No major occasion in Israel's calendar passes without an accompanying acknowledgment of sin and its need for divine forgiveness.</p>",
        "31": "<p>All Shavuot offerings are in addition to the regular tamid. The closing additive formula (<em>milelāḏ ʿōlat hattāmîḏ</em>) closes the Shavuot section as it closed the Unleavened Bread section (v23). The reiteration of additive structure at each unit's close ensures that the layered system is not misread as replacement; the tamid persists beneath all festival observance as the daily covenant foundation.</p>"
    },
    "29": {
        "1": "<p>The first day of the seventh month is a <em>yôm tərûʿâ</em> — a day of trumpet-sounding. This is Rosh Hashanah (New Year) in the later Jewish calendar, though the term itself does not appear in Numbers 29; the first-of-the-seventh-month designation is expanded in Lev 23:24 as a <em>šabbāṭôn zikrôn tərûʿâ</em> (a Sabbath of remembrance with trumpet-blowing). The seventh month is the most sacrifice-laden month of the calendar: Rosh Hashanah (1st), Yom Kippur (10th), and Sukkot (15th-22nd) are all contained within it.</p>",
        "2": "<p>The Rosh Hashanah offering: one bull, one ram, seven yearling lambs — a notably smaller sacrifice than the monthly new moon (two bulls). The reduction from the monthly new moon offering may reflect the new month's offering (v6: still required) being its own offering, with the holy assembly adding only the single-bull-ram-seven-lambs complement. The structural parallel to Yom Kippur (v8: same quantities) connects the New Year and the Day of Atonement as a unit — ten days of awe bracketed by matched offerings.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The grain offerings at the standard graduated scale: three-tenths per bull, two-tenths for the ram. The consistency of the grain-offering quantities across all major holy assemblies (Passover, Shavuot, Rosh Hashanah, Yom Kippur) establishes these four as structurally equivalent in the sacrificial system, even though their ceremonies differ significantly.</p>",
        "4": "<p>One-tenth per lamb for the seven Rosh Hashanah lambs. The grain offering total for a single holy assembly day: one bull (three-tenths) + one ram (two-tenths) + seven lambs (seven-tenths) = 1.2 ephahs of fine flour, plus approximately two hins of oil and substantial wine. The material scale of major festival observance represented significant community investment, reinforcing that covenant worship was not abstract but economically substantial.</p>",
        "5": "<p>One male goat as sin offering for Rosh Hashanah. The sin offering at the New Year frames the beginning of the new annual cycle with explicit acknowledgment of communal failure: the year begins not with presumption of righteousness but with atonement. This theological structure — atonement before celebration — characterizes Israel's entire approach to covenant renewal; the year's proper beginning is forgiveness rather than accomplishment.</p>",
        "6": "<p>All Rosh Hashanah offerings are in addition to the monthly new moon offering and the regular daily tamid. On Rosh Hashanah, then, the total offering is: tamid (2 lambs) + new moon (2 bulls, 1 ram, 7 lambs, 1 goat) + holy assembly (1 bull, 1 ram, 7 lambs, 1 goat). The day that begins the new year receives the maximum cumulative burden — an expression of intensified covenant acknowledgment at the annual threshold.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The tenth day of the seventh month is Yom Kippur — <em>wəʿinnîtem ʾet-nap̄šōtêkem</em> — the day of self-affliction. The offering law here specifies only the additional communal sacrifices; the central atonement ceremony of Yom Kippur (the two goats, the high priest's entry into the holy of holies, the scapegoat) is legislated in Lev 16. Num 29 provides the supplementary burnt offerings that accompany the Lev 16 ceremony.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The Yom Kippur offering: one bull, one ram, seven yearling lambs — identical to Rosh Hashanah (v2). The structural match between the New Year and the Day of Atonement may reflect the ancient link between the beginning of the year and its most solemn covenant renewal. The Ten Days of Awe between Rosh Hashanah and Yom Kippur in later tradition formalize this connection: the year begins with the call to repentance (trumpets) and culminates in its enactment (fasting, confession, atonement).</p>",
        "9": "<p>The grain offerings at Yom Kippur follow the same scale as all major holy assemblies. The liturgical uniformity of Yom Kippur's supplementary offerings with those of other major festivals asserts that the Day of Atonement is a festival like the others in its sacrificial structure, even though its ceremony (Lev 16) is uniquely solemn. Yom Kippur is not liturgically isolated; it participates in the same covenant-meal framework as all other appointed times.</p>",
        "10": "<p>One-tenth per lamb for the seven lambs of Yom Kippur — the same as all other holy assemblies. The uniform one-tenth-per-lamb formula creates a recognizable liturgical signature for major festival days, distinguishing them from ordinary new moons and from the extraordinary Sukkot bull-series that follows.</p>",
        "11": "<p>One male goat as sin offering for Yom Kippur — in addition to (<em>milelāḏ</em>) the Yom Kippur sin offering legislated elsewhere (Lev 16's two goats). This verse explicitly acknowledges that Num 29's goat does not replace Lev 16's elaborate goat ceremony but supplements it. Yom Kippur thus has three sin-offering components: the Lev 16 ceremony (scapegoat + offered goat for the people) plus the Num 29 sin-offering goat, making it the most richly sin-atoning day in the calendar.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The fifteenth day of the seventh month — Sukkot (Tabernacles) — begins with a <em>miqrāʾ-qōḏeš</em> and a seven-day festival with no regular work. <em>Wəḥaggōtem ḥag laYHWH šiḇʿat yāmîm</em> — you shall celebrate a festival to YHWH for seven days. Sukkot is the most elaborate festival in the sacrificial calendar, featuring the largest and most unusual offering series in all of Numbers: the decreasing-bull sacrifice from 13 to 7 over seven days plus an eighth-day closing assembly.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Day 1 of Sukkot: thirteen young bulls — the highest number of bulls in the entire calendar. The bull-count descends by one each day: 13, 12, 11, 10, 9, 8, 7 — a total of 70 bulls over the seven days. The Talmud (Sukkah 55b) interprets the 70 bulls as representing the 70 nations of the world (from Gen 10's table of nations), making Sukkot an act of global intercession: Israel sacrifices on behalf of all humanity during this festival. This interpretation gives Sukkot a universal, not merely national, theological significance.</p>",
        "14": "<p>The grain offering for Day 1 of Sukkot: three-tenths per bull (13 × three-tenths = 39/10 ephahs for the bulls alone) plus two-tenths per ram. The total grain offering for Sukkot's first day far exceeds any other festival day, reflecting the festival's extraordinary sacrificial scale. The precision of specifying three-tenths per each of the thirteen bulls — requiring a separate calculation for each animal — reflects the P tradition's mathematical thoroughness.</p>",
        "15": "<p>One-tenth per lamb for the fourteen lambs on Day 1 of Sukkot. Two rams plus fourteen lambs appear consistently across all seven days of Sukkot; only the bull count changes. The consistent ram-and-lamb complement against the decreasing bulls creates a mathematical pattern that was recognized and interpreted by later Jewish tradition as deliberately structured rather than arbitrary.</p>",
        "16": "<p>One male goat as sin offering on Day 1 of Sukkot — the same sin-offering goat present at every major festival occasion. The daily sin-offering goat throughout Sukkot's seven days means that each day of the festival includes both its own burnt-offering celebration and its own atonement component. The seven successive sin offerings ensure that the extended celebration of Sukkot does not accumulate unaddressed sin.</p>",
        "17": "<p>Day 2 of Sukkot: twelve bulls. The single-bull decrease from 13 to 12 begins the descending pattern that structures the entire festival's sacrificial logic. The symmetry of the descent — consistent single-unit reduction per day — creates a countdown toward the festival's end, each day slightly less elaborate than the previous. The descent from abundance to sufficiency mirrors the movement from harvest's plenty to covenant sufficiency.</p>",
        "18": "<p>Their grain and drink offerings for Day 2 are according to their number — the standard cross-reference formula used throughout Days 2-7 rather than restating every quantity. The formula <em>kannišpāṭ</em> — according to the ordinance/rule — establishes that the graduated grain and drink accompaniments of Num 15 govern all these offerings, creating a compact legal cross-reference system.</p>",
        "19": "<p>One goat as sin offering on Day 2 of Sukkot — the pattern holds daily. The repetition of the sin offering across all seven days of Sukkot has led scholars to read it as a daily renewal of atonement — not merely a single atoning act for the festival period but a daily covenant reset during the most elaborate festival of the year.</p>",
        "20": "<p>Day 3: eleven bulls. The decreasing series continues its mathematically regular pattern. The offering specifications for Days 3-7 (vv20-34) follow identical structural templates: N bulls + 2 rams + 14 lambs + grain offerings per number + 1 goat, all in addition to the regular tamid. The structural regularity makes the decreasing bull count the single variable that distinguishes each day from the others.</p>",
        "21": "<p>Grain and drink offerings according to the ordinance for Day 3's bulls, rams, and lambs. The kannišpāṭ formula efficiently covers the full graduated offering complement without restating what Num 15:1-12 established as the standing rule. The legal cross-reference system presupposes that users of the calendar have ch15 available; Numbers is a cumulative legal document, not a standalone code.</p>",
        "22": "<p>One goat as sin offering on Day 3. The consistent presence of the daily goat sin offering throughout Sukkot maintains the dual character of the festival — celebration and atonement in tension. Israel's liturgical calendar refuses to separate joy from acknowledgment of failure; each day of the harvest celebration is also a day of covenant humility.</p>",
        "23": "<p>Day 4: ten bulls. The decreasing sequence continues through the middle days of the festival, each day's offering slightly diminished from the previous. By Day 4, the bull count has fallen to ten — exactly half the totals implied by the series' beginning and end. The mathematical pattern suggests intentional design: the festival moves from maximum sacrificial expression to minimum.</p>",
        "24": "<p>Grain and drink offerings per the standing ordinance for Day 4. The compact cross-reference formula is used for all middle days of Sukkot; the legislative efficiency reflects the priestly compiler's assumption that readers understand the system and need only the variable (bull count) specified.</p>",
        "25": "<p>One goat as sin offering on Day 4. The daily goat ensures that the festival's middle days, despite their less elaborate offerings, maintain the atonement dimension. No day of the seven passes without the offering that addresses sin — a structural assertion that sin does not take a holiday during Israel's most celebrated festival.</p>",
        "26": "<p>Day 5: nine bulls. The descent continues past the midpoint. Days 5-7 form the closing arc of the festival's offering series, moving from nine to seven. The final number seven — matching the number of days in the festival — creates a numeric culmination: the last day's bull count equals the festival's total length, a closure by coincidence or design.</p>",
        "27": "<p>Grain and drink offerings per the ordinance for Day 5. The standing-formula cross-reference is used consistently through the middle and late days, reserving full specification only for Days 1 and 8 (where the formulaic pattern changes), bracketing the full Sukkot specification with detailed introductory and closing statements.</p>",
        "28": "<p>One goat as sin offering on Day 5. The structural persistence of the daily goat through Days 2-7 makes the goat the unchanging element across the festival's variable bull series. Amid the decreasing bulls and the constant rams and lambs, the goat sin offering is the stable atonement anchor — the offering that does not diminish or escalate but remains consistently present.</p>",
        "29": "<p>Day 6: eight bulls. One day from the end of the main festival period, the bull count reaches eight — one unit above the final seven. The anticipation of the series' completion is felt in the offering itself; the penultimate day knows its position in the sequence.</p>",
        "30": "<p>Grain and drink offerings per the ordinance for Day 6. The formula holds through the festival's final full days, maintaining legislative consistency. The entire middle section of Sukkot's offering calendar (Days 2-7) is governed by the same kannišpāṭ formula, creating a block of structural regularity that frames the unique Day 1 and Day 8 entries.</p>",
        "31": "<p>One goat as sin offering on Day 6. The daily sin offering pattern is unbroken through the entire main festival period. Six straight days of daily atonement-plus-celebration makes Sukkot the most atonement-intensive period of the year outside of Yom Kippur itself — though each day's goat is a supplement to, not a replacement for, the major annual atonement of Yom Kippur ten days earlier.</p>",
        "32": "<p>Day 7 of Sukkot: seven bulls — the terminal point of the descending series. The coincidence of Day 7 and seven bulls gives the final day of the main festival a mathematical completion: the seventh day offers seven bulls. The total bull count for the seven days: 13+12+11+10+9+8+7 = 70. The interpretation of these 70 as representing the 70 nations (Talmud Sukkah 55b) understands Israel as completing a seven-day act of intercessory sacrifice for all humanity at harvest's climax.</p>",
        "33": "<p>Grain and drink offerings per the ordinance for Day 7. The formula continues through the final day of the main Sukkot period, maintaining the legislative uniformity that has governed Days 2-7. After Day 7's closing formula, the offering specification changes format for Day 8 — signaling the structural distinction between the seven-day festival proper and the closing assembly that follows.</p>",
        "34": "<p>One goat as sin offering on Day 7. The seventh and final sin offering of the main Sukkot period completes the week-long atonement companion to the harvest celebration. Seven days of celebration paired with seven acts of atonement gives Sukkot the most complete integration of joy and repentance in the entire festival calendar — and frames the eighth-day closing assembly as an emergence into renewed covenant relationship.</p>",
        "35": "<p>Day 8 of Sukkot: <strong>שְׁמִינִי עֲצֶרֶת (Shemini Atzeret)</strong> — the Eighth Day Closing Assembly. <em>ʿAṣeret</em> — assembly, closing gathering — marks the formal conclusion of the seven-day Sukkot festival. The Talmud (Sukkah 55b) interprets this day as YHWH detaining Israel for one more day: after sacrificing 70 bulls for the 70 nations, YHWH invites Israel to linger — just the two of them — for one more intimate day. The offering (one bull, one ram, seven lambs, one goat) is the smallest of all festival offerings, contrasting dramatically with Sukkot's opening thirteen-bull day.</p>",
        "36": "<p>The Shemini Atzeret offering: one bull, one ram, seven yearling lambs. The return to the one-bull format (matching Rosh Hashanah and Yom Kippur) after the elaborate seven-day Sukkot series creates a poignant simplicity: the festival that began with thirteen bulls ends with one. The single bull may also be read as a symbol of the unique divine-human relationship being celebrated: not the universal (70 nations) but the singular covenant between YHWH and Israel.</p>",
        "37": "<p>Grain and drink offerings for Shemini Atzeret per their number. The formula applies the standard graduated scale to the closing assembly's relatively modest offering complement. The small scale of the offering by comparison with the preceding days reflects the intimacy of the final assembly: this is not public celebration but covenant quiet.</p>",
        "38": "<p>One goat as sin offering on Shemini Atzeret, in addition to the regular tamid. The closing day of the entire festival season ends with the same sin-offering goat that accompanied every major occasion throughout the calendar. Sin-offering as the closing note of the festival year suggests that even at the height of covenant intimacy, Israel's atonement needs persist — a structural humility built into the calendar's final act.</p>",
        "39": "<p><em>ʾēlleh taʿăśû laYHWH bəmôwʿădêkem</em> — these are what you shall offer to YHWH at your appointed times. The closing summary verse distinguishes these calendar-commanded offerings from voluntary ones: vow offerings (<em>nəḏārêkem</em>) and freewill offerings (<em>nidḇōtêkem</em>) are separate categories beyond the calendar requirements. The covenant calendar specifies the minimum communal worship obligation; individual devotion adds to it freely above that floor.</p>",
        "40": "<p>Moses told the Israelites everything YHWH commanded him — the compliance summary that closes the festival legislation of chs 28-29. The closing formula functions as a transitional bridge: Moses has transmitted the calendar instructions; chs 30-36 will move to vow law, Midianite war, land boundaries, and inheritance procedures. The festival calendar stands as the penultimate major legislative block of Numbers before Moses's farewell addresses in Deuteronomy.</p>"
    }
}

def main():
    data = load_comm('mkt-context', 'numbers')
    merge_comm(data, NUMBERS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'numbers', data)

main()
